			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=PVP&message.id=326#M326">1</a> of 127
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 2491 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		
				background-color: #050A0E; 
				
				 background-image: none;
				 
				background-repeat: repeat-x;
				" 
			>
			<DIV></DIV>
<DIV></DIV>
<DIV><STRONG>How to Fix EQ PvP</STRONG></DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>This is a thorough analytical essay detailing the PvP issue.&nbsp; Please read it, as I truly believe that it is an accurate way to deal with the issues plaguing the EQ PvP system.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Before I get into my post, I wanted to give a bit of background about myself in order to help orient the reader to my experience with EQ PvP.&nbsp; I am an Everquest veteran, who has played EQ since Beta phase 4.&nbsp; My home server is Tallon Zek, which I played on since the servers inception.&nbsp;&nbsp; I also tried out Sullon Zek when the server first came up and played on it for several months, until that it became obvious that the population imbalance that existed between the teams severely limited the great potential the server had.&nbsp; I went back to playing on TZ, until I finally quit several months after PoP was released.&nbsp; I returned to play on the Discord server and was one of the Champions of the server. Suffice it to say that I am very familiar with PvP in Everquest including, but not limited to, ultra-high end PvP.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The current incarnation of Everquest PvP is in an undesirable state for many reasons that will be detailed below.&nbsp; There are two solutions that both need to be implemented to solve the problem and both are vital if Everquest wants to continue to provide a significant PvP environment in the face of the upcoming competition.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The first step in solving the PvP problem should of course be to identify objectives.&nbsp; I assume in my analysis that the reason that the PvP servers exist in the first place is to satisfy consumer demand for PvP combat, as the ultimate goal of Everquest is to generate profit.&nbsp; Sony (Verant originally) correctly identified that there is a particular segment of the mmorpg player-base who is primarily motivated by PvP combat and the fun that arises from it and that these players value PvP combat above all other factors when determining their level of satisfaction with the game.&nbsp; PvPers, by definition, want PvP.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Therefore, producing a product that can satisfy this demand is potentially (obviously there are many factors here, cost, size of player base, etc) in the financial best interest of the company.&nbsp; The main problem therefore, is that the PvP servers that currently exist have probably not been performing to the desired level of financial success.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><STRONG>How does a game creator satisfy this demand and therefore meet their financial objectives?</STRONG>&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>First, one must identify the essential elements to creating a fun, healthy, and self-sufficient PvP server in order to determine what product a company can deliver to satisfy this demand.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><STRONG>What are the essential elements to creating a successful and satisfying PvP server?</STRONG></DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><STRONG>1.) Competition</STRONG>.&nbsp; The entire reason gamers choose to play on PvP servers is to face competition.&nbsp; PvPers are driven by this desire to compete with each other in order to determine who is the best player.&nbsp; The dynamic of fighting and competing with their fellow gamer is the activity that gives these players the most gaming satisfaction.&nbsp; People who have experienced intense PvP battles understand this.&nbsp; The senses are aroused, the excitement is thrilling.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><STRONG>2.) Balance</STRONG>.&nbsp; Everything starts with competition, therefore in order to create a truly healthy and competitive environment, the product must be balanced as much as possible to ensure that no particular group has a significant long term advantage over another group.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><STRONG>3.) Limited resources &amp; sufficient player population</STRONG>.&nbsp; In order to create a healthy (healthy meaning stable, long term, and satisfactory to players) PvP environment, there has to be a sufficient population for players to actually feel the threat of PvP without creating such an over-crowded environment to the point where PvP eclipses all other forms of game play.&nbsp; There must be balance here as well.&nbsp; Limited resources such as geography, items, and NPCs (xp) are vital to creating the ideal PvP environment because this ensures that players will have a motive to engage in PvP.&nbsp; Competition over resources, land, and experience points (mobs) will ensure that players PvP over these desired resources.&nbsp; PvP for the sake of PvP is fun, however, it alone will not create a long-term successful PvP environment.&nbsp; Granting players an advantage from their PvP successes, and a detriment from their losses, encourages PvP, teamwork, and contributes to the desired healthy environment.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><STRONG>4.) Low barriers to entry</STRONG>.&nbsp; People that want to PvP should be able to log onto a PvP server and fight another player within a reasonable amount of time.&nbsp; The only way to achieve this is to ensure that there is a relatively sizeable population of low-mid level players in addition to the inevitably large high-level player base.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><STRONG>Why does the current incarnation of Everquests pvp servers not deliver these elements?</STRONG></DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Each successive expansion pack has significantly affected Everquest PvP.&nbsp; The original EQ world generated a great amount of conflict, specifically because it had very limited resources, particularly in terms of experience points available for people over level 40.&nbsp; The only viable places to gain this experience were: Sol B, Lower Guk &amp; Kedge Keep.&nbsp; This created an environment with frequent PvP, but in my opinion alienated many potential PvP participants by having too limited availability of 40+ exp.&nbsp; This world also gave caster classes a significant advantage over melee classes, as melee weapons were not available to rival the damage output of the caster classes, nor was resist gear prevalent enough to make playing a pure-melee class a very effective choice for PvP.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The Kunark expansion addressed both of these problems beautifully.&nbsp; Melee items that could threaten casters arose (epics, high damage weapons) to restore class balance, and a perfect amount of land was added to disperse the population enough to ensure that there was not overcrowding.&nbsp; Balance was restored between PvP participants  or most importantly, the ability to achieve this balance through game play (certain player organizations could still dominate certain areas  as is inevitable).&nbsp; Raids were common, Pkers thrived in this still target-rich environment, and deep dungeon raid benefits were sufficient in their rewards to justify the effort, yet not unbalance PvP (Trakanon, Venril Sathir).&nbsp; The Kunark era was the most balanced PvP era in EQ history.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The Velious expansion added some very fun dynamics to PvP, while simultaneously hindering it somewhat.&nbsp; The addition of the faction cities, Skyshrine, Thurgadin &amp; Kael Drakkal created bases from which players could operate that created a dynamic PvP environment.&nbsp; Velious also introduced the first significant gear differences through the availability of Temple of Veeshan gear and high end NPC gear (Tormax, AoW, etc).&nbsp; Equal level players with significant differences in the quality of gear would be dramatically more or less effective based on their gear level.&nbsp; However, while this gear did unbalance PvP in favor of those who PvEd well, the gear differences were still not as large as the subsequent expansions.&nbsp; Despite the introduction of high end PvE raids with the intentions of gaining a large competitive advantage in PvP, Velious was still a solid expansion from the perspective of PvP because it did not dramatically unbalance the classes and it PvP was still readily available in city zones, and outdoor zones depending on the experience level of monsters.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The Shadows of Luclin expansion further developed the raid setting from Velious, and began the beginning of the significant decline in EQ PvP.&nbsp; AA abilities introduced many new class balance issues that dramatically unbalanced PvP (ranger AM, manaburn, lifeburn, etc).&nbsp; Horses (terrible for PvP) were introduced that were immune to snare and provided easy methods of escape for people who wanted to avoid PvP.&nbsp; The added landmass further spread out an already thinning population and the introduction of safe zones such as the Nexus and Bazaar provided a solace for hundreds of people at any given time from the threat of PvP.&nbsp; Luclin however, although devastating to a healthy PvP environment did not destroy it to nearly the same extent as PoP.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The Planes of Power expansion is a PvE expansion in the fullest meaning of the term.&nbsp; The additional levels of 61-65, new spells, new AAs, new gear, new raid encounters, flag requirements and teleport books, and of course the substitution of towns for an all-encompassing safe zone of PoK was too much for the weakening PvP system to bear; PoP was the straw that broke EQ PvPs back.&nbsp; Classes became hugely unbalanced, equal level character power discrepancies grew even larger, and flags provided a convenient method for guilds with a PvE advantage to ruin PvE encounters of their competitors to keep the status quo of gear divisions.&nbsp; All these points served to hugely damage the fundamentally important PvP element of competition.&nbsp; The ability for players to compete now became almost entirely based on their ability to PvE successfully, instead of PvPing successfully.&nbsp; Group tactics and individual ability was replaced by AA abilities and gear to the point where skill could not overcome the difference.&nbsp; This is the fundamental reason that PvP servers have degenerated to the point now where PvP is an afterthought, something to distract people in between the uber PvE raids and character advancement.&nbsp; Hence, the solution to this problem is obvious: return to what works and create a complimentary rule-set to enhance the PvP environment.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><STRONG>To recap, what are the problems with current EQ PvP? </STRONG></DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><STRONG>Competition has declined across all level ranges.</STRONG>&nbsp; The increased landmass means that new players can level up and literally never see PvP unless they actively look for it (the fear factor has been removed).&nbsp; Safe zones and horses have ensured that people can flee from PvP easily with virtual impunity.&nbsp; Imbalance (explained below) has decreased competition by removing the fear of death for the most overpowered beneficiaries.&nbsp;&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><STRONG>Relative balance is gone.</STRONG>&nbsp;&nbsp; Classes are hugely unbalanced; AA abilities &amp; massive gear discrepancies ensure that certain guilds dedicated to high-end PvE have massive advantages that completely remove the fear of death from PvP for them and increases the amount of griefing.&nbsp; Certain classes (SKs) are far more prevalent than other classes, because the power gap is so hugely obvious.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><STRONG>The fundamental mechanism to improve ones PvPing is now PvE.</STRONG>&nbsp; Due to the huge gear discrepancies that can exist, you can only compete at high end PvP if you put in years of effort into developing your character.&nbsp; This ensures a dwindling number of players (larger barriers to entry) because the ability gap for the minimum power level people need to compete grows larger and larger.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><STRONG>How can EQ PvP be fixed to provide the essential elements to a healthy PvP server that players (and therefore the company) want?</STRONG></DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><STRONG>So what is the solution that addresses these issues?</STRONG>&nbsp;&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>There are two separate issues as far as Sony is concerned.&nbsp; What do we do with the live servers and how to we increase our market share of PvP minded individuals in the face of the upcoming competition (WoW)?&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><STRONG>What do we do with the live servers?</STRONG></DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The current PvP servers are 90% blue  meaning very little PvP occurs.&nbsp; Changing the composition of these servers dramatically will probably mean you end up losing just as many people as you may gain.&nbsp; The servers have been PvE focused for so long, that the current players on these servers generally PvE first and PvP as an after thought.&nbsp; Therefore, the solution here is to:</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>1.) Try to balance the classes &amp; resists.&nbsp; This is an uphill battle, because classes are so unbalanced now that it is difficult to come up with solutions to help  especially given the disparities that exist in gear.&nbsp; The key thing that needs nerfing is Deathtouch (SKs), and pure melees need some sort of a boost  I would assume damage boost.&nbsp; Look to other posters for their feedback, mine is primarily concerned with the real solution (below).&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>2.) Remove the safe zones except the bazaar.&nbsp; This will dramatically increase the amount of PvP that occurs by people traveling to and from their destination, will make travel more dangerous, and will add spice to servers in desperate need.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Other than that, there isnt much that I can think of that can be done without knowing what your (Sonys) objectives and technical capabilities are.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><STRONG>What do we do to truly capture the PvPer market?</STRONG></DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The difficulties I outlined above are pervasive and are very difficult to address on the live servers; therefore the ideal solution is to create a new server.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>As a number of players have said, the server outlined below would be close to the <STRONG>ideal</STRONG> PvP environment.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>This new server needs to consist of the following rules:</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>1.) Either two hardcoded teams with each class and each race available for both and with a population cap (if possible) that maintains a 60/40 of accounts, or a server with no teams where everyone can be killed by everyone else.&nbsp; Servers naturally gravitate towards two teams - accommodate this desire and ensure a relatively balanced population count or eliminate it altogether so the server becomes guild v. guild (either method can work).&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>2.)&nbsp; XP loss on any death, including PvP from someone within 8 levels, drowning, etc, equal to that of a normal XP death.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>3.)&nbsp; Only have the expansions up to Velious enabled (or even just Kunark - Dev team discretion  or launch with Kunark, and if need be, release Velious later).&nbsp; There is more than enough content in these expansions to satisfy people interested in PvP.&nbsp; People would come to this server for a fun, challenging and rewarding PvP environment, not to advance their character and become uber.&nbsp; I guarantee that EQ in the original state of Pre-Luclin creates a fantastic and fun PvP environment that can be enjoyed for years - even when people reach the level cap, (especially when people reach the level cap - then their primary focus will be PvP).&nbsp; Do not launch additional expansions.&nbsp; The main content should be static, only tweak if necessary.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>4.)&nbsp; Enable item loot of one item per PvP death (even in bags) with the exception of epics - and remove no drop gear.&nbsp; Item loot is the second most important rule that can be implemented on this server (behind expansion choice), but it needs to also have the Firiona Vie ruleset where there are very very very few no drop items.&nbsp; To create a balance between those who PvE and those who PvP (and incentives for both groups), the ability to gain items and to lose items needs to be a real threat.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>Now, in order to properly balance the server so melee classes are not hurt too badly by item loot, there should also be additional rules to help melees (but apply to all classes):</DIV>
<DIV>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Player can choose 2-4 items (dev discretion) that are unlootable upon death</DIV>
<DIV>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Or the only items not lootable upon death are epics (normal weapon slot items should be lootable.</DIV>
<DIV>I personally recommend the first solution.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>5.) PvP targets within 20 levels.&nbsp; Item loot within 8 levels.&nbsp; Exp loss within 8 levels.&nbsp; Noob ganking is not to be encouraged, but a wide enough range should be granted to ensure that spies and the like are easily dealt with.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><STRONG>Why these core rules?<BR></STRONG>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>They ensure a relatively balanced playing field with a semi-limited geography that balances the needs of PvE and exp with those of PvP.&nbsp; They also ensure that players are incentivized to PvP through the ability to loot items from other players, while fearing death themselves for the fear of item and XP loss.&nbsp; This server also strongly encourages team work, as people will need to work together to not lose their items, and it also ensures that the item discrepancy between players does not get so large that people can grief others with impunity.&nbsp; By its very nature, item loss promotes a circulation of items and therefore more competition.&nbsp; It would also have low barriers to entry because level 60s couldnt kill level 6s, and with content capped at Velious, it would be far easier to catch up in order to participate in the fun high-end combat.&nbsp; This server would deliver (strongly) the four essential elements to a successful PvP server: competition, balance, limited resources &amp; strong population (I seriously think it will be so popular youd need to make two or more of these) and of course low barriers to entry to ensure that people who want to join in on the fun can and will.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>These additional rules are not as important to the central core tenets of gameplay, but should also be implemented (or altered):</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>5.) Code it so guilds &amp; raids are immune to player AE's from players in their raid if the server is FFA and not hardcoded</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>6.) Create a Sullen Zek style leaderboard - but remove the points that accrue from old tokens - only new kills should give points.&nbsp; Reward people for actively killing.&nbsp; Code it so you lose points if you repeatedly kill people within a given amount of time - similar to the SZ ruleset.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>7.)&nbsp; One character per account</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>8.)&nbsp; Zone control map similar to SZ's</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>9.)&nbsp; In game rewards from turning in points (tokens) - clickable items such as non-rechargable pre-nerf pumice or golem wands (very expensive) or high end potions would be great incentives</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>10.)&nbsp; Debuffs 50% more effective in PvP</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>11.)&nbsp; Nukes 66% effectiveness in PvP</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>12.)&nbsp; Faction hits in hometown killings</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>13.)&nbsp; No binding in dungeons</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>14.) Naked corpses disappear when looted in PvP</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>15.)&nbsp; Rogues can pick pockets of players - make it worth their while too - 10% of total cash, etc (no safe zones except cities - so people can get it back)</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>16.) Standard 20 lvl buff rule</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>17.) Hide and invis cause loss of target</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>18.) /consider gives fairly accurate reading - 10+ levels lower, light blue 6-9 levels lower, blue 1-5 levels lower, white same level, yellow 1-4 levels over, red 5+ levels over</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>19.) No training, excessive swearing, etc.&nbsp; GM support strongly desired.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Additional rules can of course be applied per dev team discretion.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><STRONG>Conclusion</STRONG><BR>The goal is to establish a long-term PvP server that gives players what they want: a competitive, fun, challenging and balanced server that will be shaped through the deeds of the players against each other  not solely through the PvE raiding abilities.&nbsp; Character development should be important, but not the central characteristic that defines PvP.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I seriously hope the dev team strongly considers this idea and that the player base thinks about the big picture long enough to understand why this would work.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Tryndamere Elfbane, Human Retribution</DIV>
<DIV>Kilithyr Tekndius, The Revelation</DIV>
<DIV>Ryltarr Daemorsith, The Revelation</DIV>
<DIV>Narodnika Sopowah, Discordia</DIV>
<DIV>Trindamere the Executioner, Champion of Discord</DIV>	
		</td></tr>
