			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=PVP&message.id=340#M340">10</a> of 127
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 2185 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<P>Well, PDM recruited me every step of the way and I never wanted to join - I prefer to be the underdog.&nbsp; To me, joining the winning team is hardly exciting.&nbsp; I did quite well against them through my entire EQ time on TZ really up until PoP.&nbsp; I'm not one to sit on 8+ hour raids all day so I can get an item, I always spent my time killing people.</P>
<P>Yes, EQ is a PvE game, which is exactly my point - if Sony wants to create a fun PvP environment, they need to try to do something to change that model as much as possible.&nbsp; PvE based games do not make for the best PvP games.&nbsp; My post outlines various ways to achieve these desired results - namely item loot with FV item no drop rules.&nbsp; Item loot set in the Velious expansion rewards both PvPers and PvEers as it would create a circulation of items that would create a fun environment.&nbsp; </P>
<P>In an mmorpg, yes you build your character through PvE and advance, however, to create a PvP environment that is truely competitive and therefore fun, the primary mechanism for fun should be the PvP itself - not the PvE.&nbsp; This can only arise over the long term when there is incentive to PvP (such as item loot), and when all parties involved have some risk.&nbsp; Remove the fear of death, and PvP becomes mundane and boring.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV></DIV>	
