			<br>
			
				<img src="/i/p.gif" height=8 width=150 border=0 alt=""><br>
				
			<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=1353'>







<img src="/eq/i/icons/Classes/magician.gif" border=0 alt=""/></a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=PVP&message.id=354#M354">19</a> of 127
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 2084 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<br><blockquote><hr>Trynd wrote:<br><EM>Item loot encourages bottom feeding and ganking. If there is a reward for killing people who have no chance in defeating you people will do it, to the exclusion of getting into a fight where they might lose. By the same token unless there is a definite loss from a PvP death there can be no reasonable reward for killing someone in PvP. XP loss isn't really a problem when you have a 96% rez available which any sort of long-term server will have, so giving people the ability to "buy" items with kills won't work; you'll just have people trading off killing each other then getting a rez until everyone can get whatever they want. That's why I don't think item loot or item rewards for PvP will work.</em> <DIV> </div><DIV>Killing the same person repeatedly will actually decrease your point total - the timeframe where this occurs can be tweaked.  People kept saying Discord sucked because you could make a level one frog in Grobb, run him to Guk and kill him to gain points over and over - an obvious exploit.  This problem was greatly overstated, I think the Darkenbane crew killed the handful of people who tried to do this and the problem was solved - I didn't even worry about it, I just killed everyone I could.  The fear that people will exploit a point reward system to gain relatively minor items (resist gear, potions, whatever) is similiarly overstated if the ruleset is properly developed to make this difficult.  Not only should the points necessary for rewards not be cheap, but if you kill the same person three times and then start losing points (say you need to wait 3 hours or something to gain positive points from them again) then this would be too much of a hassle to be worth it.  It would be far more efficient to go kill real enemies.</div><DIV> </div><DIV>As far as item loot encouraging ganking - that is actually the point.  Ganking means that players who play on this server will be afraid.  They'll always be looking over their shoulder, they'll travel in groups, and they'll be loyal to their friends.  Kill or be killed - this is what creates the fun pvp dynamic - this is the same reason that Discord was so much fun and was so intense.  The penalty for death was massive!</div><DIV> </div><DIV>Plus, in the long term, resist gear will become available, and there will develop a relative equilibrium in the circulation of gear.  Word will get out when some people start getting some uber gear and gank squads will form to go kill them.  How is that not awesome?  This keeps everyone on their toes!  This would be the essence of what makes pvp fun!</div><DIV> </div><DIV> </div><br><hr></blockquote><br><br><br>The problem is that for a full-time production server this won't happen.  As some people advance in PvE at first there will be resistance from the rest of the server, but over time people will join them in the theory that "if you can't beat them ...."  This will lead to one guild having a huge advantage over the rest of the server and be able to use that advantage to keep the rest down.  Having item loot makes this so much easier because not only are they able to deny better gear to their opponents they are able to actually downgrade them at the same time.  If you want examples look at the migration towards x-team guilds on Vallon and Tallon Zek or the migration to the evil team on Sullon Zek.  For a short-term server like Discord that's fine because you know when the server resets you'll get another bite at the apple, so to speak, but if it's going to be around for awhile ... no-one likes getting the short-end of the stick, and the majority of people will go to where they feel they'll be safer and more powerful.
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							Menre Nar'tredok<br>Arch Mage of the Crimson Praetorian<br>Blood and Honor!
							</div>
								
		</td></tr>
